<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-292-154  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 292 154.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  May 22 1989 n249 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bell Atlantic pushes toward intelligent net. (Network.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rockwell, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>President and CEO Raymond Smith of Bell Atlantic Corp envisionsthe deployment of the intelligent network in the early 1990s.andO;With its 'smart' digital switches and databases and its capacityfor user-network interface, this network is viewed by Smith, whosecompany has increased its cash flow by $1 billion a year since1985, as the key to staying competitive with foreign nations likeEngland, France and Germany.andP;  Fiber optic cable is at the heart ofintelligent network development.andP;  Smith hopes to increase the300,000 miles of fiber in Bell Atlantic territory to 50 percent ofoutside plant by 1990.andP;  High-definition television (HDTV) is thekey to consumer adoption of the advanced network in his view, buthe believes that greater freedoms must be granted to the Bellholding companies in terms of manufacturing and informationservices if they are to meet customer demands for moresophisticated services.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (forecasts).andO;Ticker:    BEL.andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsInformation ServicesGoals and ObjectivesHigh-Definition TelevisionUser InterfaceForeign CompetitionNetworks.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Raymond Smith (portrait)Person:    Smith, Raymond W. (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>